abstract:
&lt;p&gt;Climate action remains insufficient to meet Paris Agreement targets, creating an urgent need to understand how to effectively motivate individual pro-environmental behavior. While traditional approaches emphasize the direct impact of individual behavioral changes, we investigate whether highlighting the indirect effects of social contagion—where one's behavior influences others—can more effectively drive climate action.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Through a field experiment with 579 business school students participating in Climate Collage workshops, we compare two message framings: a "direct effect" approach emphasizing personal carbon footprint reduction, and an "indirect effect" approach emphasizing how visible behavior changes can influence others and create new social norms. We measure both pro-environmental behaviors (PEBs) and behavioral visibility (sharing behaviors on social media and with others).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our findings reveal that while both framings equally increase PEBs, the indirect framing significantly increases participants' sharing of environmental behaviors on social media three weeks post-intervention. Importantly, this effect is moderated by individual psychological traits: the indirect framing is most effective for individuals high in negative environmental outcome affect and low in resistance to coercion. Post-hoc analysis shows that indirect framing better alleviates negative emotions elicited by climate education.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These findings contribute to institutional theory's microfoundations by demonstrating that awareness of one's role as an influencer can motivate behavior change, though message tailoring based on individual traits is critical. Our results offer practical insights for designing high-impact climate education interventions that leverage social contagion effects.&lt;/p&gt;
